{"runId":"deepseek-deepseek-v4-flash@2026-07-18T05-49-33-860Z","slug":"security-agent-model-router","locale":"zh","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash","modelPath":"deepseek-deepseek-v4-flash","createdAt":"2026-07-18T05:51:52.534Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2026-06-30--security-agent-model-router/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2026-06-30--security-agent-model-router/zh/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/security-agent-model-router/zh/deepseek-deepseek-v4-flash/2026-07-18T05-49-33-860Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"a64bd6363b4cad4722638e6078e81337e5ea158658519ad0c34a97e2e691227f","outputHash":"5e811ed39263caa434be0dcbf2ff8a90d4d7adbe451fe2120a778c92922c52b2","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that security agents should be selected via model routers—matching each task to the most appropriate model based on budget, tool surface, and failure modes—rather than relying on global model rankings or leaderboards. The author presents evaluation results from agentic security workflows (e.g., vulnerability sweeps, planning, tool use) showing that cheap models often outperform premium ones in specific scenarios, and that many apparent model failures stem from system integration issues like harness or artifact handling. Key metrics include deterministic scores, judge-assessed behavior, cost, and guard failures, with DeepSeek Flash emerging as a cost-efficient frontier option and GPT-5.6 Sol leading in raw performance. The tone is analytical and engineering-focused, aimed at practitioners building security agents, and uses the recurring metaphor of “routing” versus “leaderboard” thinking to frame the core design decision.","totalInputTokens":15612,"totalOutputTokens":10105,"totalCacheReadTokens":3840,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":127640,"totalCostUsd":0.004488232,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash","chunkSiz