{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-07-18T05-55-18-445Z","slug":"security-agent-model-router","locale":"it","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-07-18T05:55:25.665Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2026-06-30--security-agent-model-router/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2026-06-30--security-agent-model-router/it/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/security-agent-model-router/it/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-07-18T05-55-18-445Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"a64bd6363b4cad4722638e6078e81337e5ea158658519ad0c34a97e2e691227f","outputHash":"c2093be4571cd188e0ba1e85f1b756e56215439475a7779424fcc777630c74c3","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.1,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that choosing a security‑agent LLM should be framed as a **routing problem**, not a simple leaderboard ranking: the right model must be assigned to a specific task, budget, and tool set while being monitored for safety and evidence‑preserving behavior. It presents a product‑focused evaluation suite covering discovery, planning, tool use, and system integration, and shows that cheap or local models can outperform premium ones when judged on scoped, evidence‑backed outputs and cost‑efficiency. Detailed results for seven “model routes” (e.g., GPT‑5.6 Sol, Gemini Flash, DeepSeek Flash) illustrate a cost‑quality frontier, emphasizing that engineers should start with the frontier models and then upscale only for the failure modes relevant to their use case. The tone is analytical and tutorial‑like, using the metaphor of “routing” versus “ranking” and repeatedly framing the discussion as a practical engineering decision for security‑agent developers.","totalInputTokens":15165,"totalOutputTokens":8631,"totalCacheReadTokens":4352,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":5648,"totalCostUsd":0.002145015,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","chunkSize":"18p","totalChunks":6,"totalInputTokens":15165,"totalOutputTokens":8631,"totalCacheReadTokens":4352,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":5648,"totalCostUsd":0.002145015,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","chunks":[{"index":0,"inputTokens":1835,"outputTokens":680,"cacheReadTokens":0,"cacheWriteTokens":0,"durationMs":447,"costUsd":0.000193965},{"index":1,"inputTokens":2519,"outputTokens":1531,"cacheReadTokens":1152,"cacheWriteTokens":0,"durationMs":1086,"costUsd":0.000373821},{"index":2,"inputTokens":2769,"outputTokens":1521,"cacheReadTokens":896,"cacheWriteTokens":0,"durationMs":971,"costUsd":0.000381771},{"index":3,"inputTokens":2876,"outputTokens":1981,"cacheReadTokens":1152,"cacheWriteTokens":0,"durationMs":1270,"costUsd":0.000468744},{"index":4,"inputTokens":2510,"outputTokens":1145,"cacheReadTokens":0,"cacheWriteTokens":0,"durationMs":705,"costUsd":0.00030398999999999997},{"index":5,"inputTokens":2656,"outputTokens":1773,"cacheReadTokens":1152,"cacheWriteTokens":0,"durationMs":1169,"costUsd":0.000422724}]}}
{"runId":"deepseek-deepseek-v4-flash@2026-07-18T05-52-25-295Z","slug":"security-agent-model-router","locale":"es","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash","modelPath":"deepseek-deepseek-v4-flash","createdAt":"2026-07-18T05:55:36.726Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2026-06-30--security-agent-model-router/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2026-06-30--security-agent-model-router/es/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/security-agent-model-router/es/deepseek-deepseek-v4-flash/2026-07-18T05-52-25-295Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"a64bd6363b4cad4722638e6078e81337e5ea158658519ad0c34a97e2e691227f","outputHash":"7360bbc03c2eefe259ec8eaf58dd32fc48aae970946a6fbc950b9f0d2b72d56c","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that selecting a model for a security agent should be treated as a routing problem—matching the model to the task, budget, and tool surface—rather than a leaderboard problem of picking the \"best\" model. It presents results from a product-shaped eval suite for security-agency tasks, showing that cheap models like DeepSeek Flash can be highly cost-effective despite lower scores, while premium models like GPT-5.6 Sol excel but at greater expense and with stability trade-offs. The tone is analytical and critical of simplistic benchmarking, using framing devices such as the \"bar chart with a winner\" to dismiss model rankings and the \"cost-quality frontier\" to emphasize trade-offs. The intended audience is engineers building production security agents who need practical routing decisions, not marketing-friendly rankings.","totalInputTokens":16020,"totalOutputTokens":23812,"totalCacheReadTokens":6144,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":177187,"totalCostUsd":0.008067203200000001,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash","chunkSize":"18p","totalChunks":6,"totalInputTokens":16020,"totalOutputTokens":23812,"totalCacheReadTo