{"runId":"deepseek-deepseek-v4-flash@2026-07-18T05-52-34-243Z","slug":"security-agent-model-router","locale":"de","model":"deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash","modelPath":"deepseek-deepseek-v4-flash","createdAt":"2026-07-18T05:55:56.472Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2026-06-30--security-agent-model-router/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2026-06-30--security-agent-model-router/de/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/security-agent-model-router/de/deepseek-deepseek-v4-flash/2026-07-18T05-52-34-243Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"a64bd6363b4cad4722638e6078e81337e5ea158658519ad0c34a97e2e691227f","outputHash":"969eacffb045cfef2b5641d91153168f62d456d4e22b184681111cb1c086ef2e","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"The article argues that security agents should evaluate models through routing decisions rather than leaderboard rankings, because different models excel at different tasks under varying cost and safety constraints. It presents a practical eval suite for security agent workflows (e.g., Juice Shop, Docker labs) that grades not only final outputs but also tool usage, scope adherence, and evidence handling. The analysis identifies a cost-quality frontier with two standout routes—DeepSeek Flash for low cost and GPT-5.6 Sol for maximum score—and emphasizes that the real engineering question is which model to route a specific task to, not which model is globally best. The tone is analytical and engineering-focused, using a recurring \"routing vs. ranking\" frame to critique conventional benchmarks. Intended audience: security engineers and AI practitioners building agentic systems.","totalInputTokens":15066,"totalOutputTokens":23086,"totalCacheReadTokens":4864,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":187051,"totalCostUsd":0.0079059792,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash","chunkSize":"18p","totalChunks":6,"totalInputTokens":15066,"totalOutputTo